  <text>
      <front>
         <p>1875 June 19? to McLean<note xml:id="ftn2-221" place="foot" n="221">ATL Object #1001405 from MS-Papers-0032-0222.</note>
         </p>
      </front>
      <body>
         <p rend="end">Napier</p>
         <p rend="end">Saty. 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi>
            <note xml:id="ftn2-222" place="foot" n="222">This letter clearly relates to the 21 July letter, and June is the only month in 1875 that has a Saturday 19th.</note>
         </p>
         <p>My Dear Sir Donald,</p>
         <p>After a great deal of “revolving in mind &amp; coming to no satisfactory conclusion”—I have written the enclosed,<note xml:id="ftn2-223" place="foot" n="223"> Apparently a paper about the Maori Lexicon, not now among the McLean papers.</note> which (as I take it) serves to place the matter of the Lexn. fairly before you in a few plain words.—I have only <hi rend="italic">one </hi>purpose in the matter, to aid all that I can while I may.</p>
         <p>I do not know where you are <hi rend="italic">now</hi>: but I post this. And when I hear of your arrival in town will wait upon you &amp; <hi rend="italic">see your face once more</hi>! —</p>
         <p>             I am,</p>
         <p>       My Dear Sir Donald</p>
         <p>     Yours Very truly</p>
         <p>                     W. Colenso.</p>
      </body>
  </text>
